Here are both approaches for .NET MAUI Shell navigation:

**1. Register the route:**
```csharp
// AppShell.xaml.cs
Routing.RegisterRoute("productdetails", typeof(ProductDetailsPage));
```

**2. Navigate — simple string parameter:**
```csharp
// ProductListViewModel.cs (or code-behind)
async void OnProductSelected(Product product)
{
    await Shell.Current.GoToAsync($"productdetails?productId={product.Id}");
}
```

**3. Navigate — passing the full object:**
```csharp
async void OnProductSelected(Product product)
{
    var parameters = new Dictionary<string, object>
    {
        { "product", product }
    };
    await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("productdetails", parameters);
}
```

**4. Receive both on the ViewModel with `IQueryAttributable`:**
```csharp
public class ProductDetailsViewModel : ObservableObject, IQueryAttributable
{
    public void ApplyQueryAttributes(IDictionary<string, object> query)
    {
        // Approach 1: string parameter (arrives as string)
        if (query.TryGetValue("productId", out var idObj))
        {
            string productId = idObj.ToString();
            // fetch product from service using productId
        }

        // Approach 2: full object (arrives as-is, just cast)
        if (query.TryGetValue("product", out var obj) && obj is Product product)
        {
            // use product directly — no fetch needed
            Name = product.Name;
            Price = product.Price;
        }
    }
}
```

**5. Wire the ViewModel to the page:**
```csharp
public partial class ProductDetailsPage : ContentPage
{
    public ProductDetailsPage(ProductDetailsViewModel vm)
    {
        InitializeComponent();
        BindingContext = vm;
    }
}
```

**Key differences:**

| | String param | Object param |
|---|---|---|
| **Syntax** | Query string (`?key=val`) | `Dictionary<string, object>` overload |
| **Arrives as** | `string` | Original type (cast it) |
| **Use when** | Simple IDs, deep links, URLs | Complex objects already in memory |
| **Serializable** | Yes (appears in URI) | No (in-memory only) |

> **Tip:** String parameters also work with `[QueryProperty]` attributes, but `IQueryAttributable` is preferred — it gives you a single entry point, works for both strings and objects, and keeps navigation logic in the ViewModel.
